          Programming note:=C2=A0Money Stuff will be off tomorrow and next =
week, back on April 10. Empirically this is expected to=C2=A0dampen market =
volatility, though this is not investing advice and past results may not be=
 representative of future performance. But enjoy a nice quiet week in finan=
cial markets without me, have fun, try not to break anything.

 =20
   =20
      Bloodbath: Beyond
   =20
 =20

In early February, Bed Bath & Beyond Inc. was skating pretty close to bankr=
uptcy. If it had filed for bankruptcy, the expected outcome would be that i=
ts shares of stock would be worthless and its creditors would end up owning=
 the company; probably the company   would have liquidated, stores would ha=
ve closed, and the creditors would get pennies on the dollar. But it was no=
t there yet: At the beginning of February, Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock traded =
at around $3 per share, for an equity market capitalization of around $300 =
million to $400 million, because shareholders held out some hope. On a bank=
ruptcy filing, that value would=C2=A0more or less immediately jump to zero.
  [1]

But then an investor called Hudson Bay Capital came to Bed Bath & Beyond wi=
th an idea.
  [2]
=C2=A0The idea is less an idea of corporate finance and more an idea of mat=
h. What if, instead of taking the stock down from $3 to $0 immediately with=
 a bankruptcy filing, Bed Bath=C2=A0slowly=C2=A0took the stock down from $3=
 to $0? What if Bed Bath just=C2=A0sold=C2=A0stock until the price hit zero=
? Sell a little stock at $3, the stock drops to $2.90. Sell a little more a=
t $2.90, it drops to $2.80. Sell a little more at $2.80, it drops to $2.70.=
 Keep selling some stock each day, raising a bit of money and driving the p=
rice down some more. It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Zeno=E2=80=99s paradox: If you keep =
selling stock as the price gets closer and closer to zero, you can keep rai=
sing money and never run out.
Well, really, eventually one of three things will happen
  [3]
:
=09The price gets to zero. Nobody wants to buy it anymore.=C2=A0You have ra=
ised some money, but not enough to pay back the debt and keep the company a=
float, and you go bankrupt. Oh well!=C2=A0=09You raise enough money, from s=
elling stock as the price goes down, to pay down your debt, get some room t=
o operate, and turn the business around.
  [4]
=C2=A0You put out an announcement like =E2=80=9Chey everything is great now=
, problem solved.=E2=80=9D The stock starts going=C2=A0up:=C2=A0The busines=
s has improved, the threat of bankruptcy is gone, and also=C2=A0you don=E2=
=80=99t have to sell stock anymore because things are fine.=09That doesn=E2=
=80=99t happen, but the stock starts going up anyway, because Bed Bath is s=
ort of a meme stock and sometimes meme stocks go up for no reason, or for c=
ounterintuitive reasons, or just because they do something weird and make s=
ome news. And then you get to sell more stock and raise more money and keep=
 this going for a while. Probably you eventually end up in Outcome=C2=A01 o=
r Outcome 2, but I suppose it is theoretically possible to be in this state=
 forever.
  [5]



This sounds strictly=C2=A0better than filing for bankruptcy in early Februa=
ry.=C2=A0Outcome 2 is straightforwardly good. Outcome 3 is, you know, weird=
, but sort of looks like Outcome 2. Outcome 1 is bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0you go =
bankrupt =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s no=C2=A0worse=C2=A0than filing for=
 bankruptcy immediately, and in some ways it is better: You=E2=80=99ve rais=
ed some money, which means that your creditors get a better recovery, and y=
ou=E2=80=99ve delayed the bankruptcy so your employees can keep their jobs =
a while longer. Of course the money you raised comes from somewhere: It com=
es from people who=C2=A0bought=C2=A0stock from you on the way to zero, at p=
rices higher than zero, and=C2=A0they=C2=A0might=C2=A0feel=C2=A0aggrieved t=
hat they threw their money into this bonfire. This is worse for=C2=A0them=
=C2=A0than just filing for bankruptcy immediately. But they are equity inve=
stors =E2=80=94=C2=A0realistically, they are meme-stock investors =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and it=E2=80=99s their job to take weird risks.
Sounds pretty good, right?
  [6]
=C2=A0Why doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0every company do this, instead of filing for=
 bankruptcy? Well I think there are a few things that you need to manage re=
ally carefully if you want to try this:
=09If you just go out and=C2=A0say=C2=A0you=E2=80=99re going to do it, then=
 investors will reasonably say =E2=80=9Cwait you=E2=80=99re selling stock u=
ntil the stock goes to zero, why should I buy it at a price higher than zer=
o?=E2=80=9D And so the stock collapses to zero immediately, you never raise=
 any money, and it doesn=E2=80=99t work. If you want to try this, you have =
to be somewhat opaque about it, so that investors actually buy the stock.=
=09Conversely, if you are=C2=A0too=C2=A0opaque about it, and lots of invest=
ors buy the stock at high prices and you end up in Outcome 1 anyway, those =
investors will sue you and the US Securities and Exchange Commission will h=
ave a lot of questions and you will get in a lot of trouble. If you want to=
 try this, you have to have=C2=A0really good disclosure, so that investors =
who=C2=A0buy the stock can=E2=80=99t say they were deceived. You want that =
disclosure to be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0accurate and complete, but confusing? I dun=
no, it=E2=80=99s a weird=C2=A0needle to thread.=09You need to be somewhat s=
killful about selling the stock. You can=E2=80=99t just mash the sell butto=
n every day; you have to have a sense of the market, sell a lot when there=
=E2=80=99s a lot of demand, step back when there isn=E2=80=99t. The price o=
f the stock here is going to be a delicate thing, and it takes skill to wri=
ng as much money out of it as possible.

Bed Bath took Hudson Bay up on the idea, I   wrote about it a   few   times=
, and it was great fun. What I said above is=C2=A0not=C2=A0how the deal is =
officially described.
  [7]
 As a technical matter, Bed Bath was not selling any stock into the market;=
 instead, Bed Bath was selling big slabs of=C2=A0convertible preferred stoc=
k=C2=A0to Hudson Bay (and some other investors who came along in the deal),=
 and then Hudson Bay might =E2=80=94=C2=A0at its option =E2=80=94 convert s=
ome of that preferred into common stock. And then it might hold that common=
 stock, or=C2=A0sell it into the market. But that=E2=80=99s Hudson Bay=E2=
=80=99s problem, not Bed Bath=E2=80=99s. But the preferred converts into co=
mmon at a=C2=A0discount to the current trading price, meaning that it alway=
