10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em>=C2=A0Mo=
ney Stuff will be off tomorrow and next week, back on April 10. Empirically=
 this is expected to=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/31011090.260442/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2Z=
tP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQzODYyNTY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe800fa68" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">dampen market volatility</a>, though this is not i=
nvesting advice and past results may not be representative of future perfor=
mance. But enjoy a nice quiet week in financial markets without me, have fu=
n, try not to break anything.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bloodbath: Beyond</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In early February, Bed Bath &amp; Beyond Inc. =
was skating pretty close to bankruptcy. If it had filed for bankruptcy, the=
 expected outcome would be that its shares of stock would be worthless and =
its creditors would end up owning the company; probably the company <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31011090.260442/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMjcvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5=
b25kLWZhbHRlcnMtaW4tZWZmb3J0LXRvLWZpbmQtYnV5ZXItaW4tYmFua3J1cHRjeT9jbXBpZD1=
CQkQwMzMwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldH=
RlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBb208ad76" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  would have liquidated</a>, stores would have cl=
osed, and the creditors would get pennies on the dollar. But it was not the=
re yet: At the beginning of February, Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock traded at ar=
ound $3 per share, for an equity market capitalization of around $300 milli=
on to $400 million, because shareholders held out some hope. On a bankruptc=
y filing, that value would=C2=A0more or less immediately jump to zero.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then an investor called Hudson Bay Capital=
 came to Bed Bath &amp; Beyond with an idea.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hre=
f=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inl=
ine-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The idea is less an idea of corporate finance and more an idea of=
 math. What if, instead of taking the stock down from $3 to $0 immediately =
with a bankruptcy filing, Bed Bath=C2=A0<em>slowly=C2=A0</em>took the stock=
 down from $3 to $0? What if Bed Bath just=C2=A0<em>sold</em>=C2=A0stock un=
til the price hit zero? Sell a little stock at $3, the stock drops to $2.90=
. Sell a little more at $2.90, it drops to $2.80. Sell a little more at $2.=
80, it drops to $2.70. Keep selling some stock each day, raising a bit of m=
oney and driving the price down some more. It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31011090.260442/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53=
aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvWmVubyUyN3NfcGFyYWRveGVzI0FjaGlsbGVzX2FuZF90aGVfdG9=
ydG9pc2U/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe5044c99" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">Zeno=E2=80=99s paradox</a>: If you keep selling stock as the price get=
s closer and closer to zero, you can keep raising money and never run out.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, really, eventually one of three things w=
ill happen<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The price gets to zero. Nobody wants =
to buy it anymore.=C2=A0You have raised some money, but not enough to pay b=
ack the debt and keep the company afloat, and you go bankrupt. Oh well!=C2=
=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You raise enough money, from s=
elling stock as the price goes down, to pay down your debt, get some room t=
o operate, and turn the business around.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You put out an announcement like =E2=80=9Chey everything is great=
 now, problem solved.=E2=80=9D The stock starts going=C2=A0<em>up:=C2=A0</e=
m>The business has improved, the threat of bankruptcy is gone, and also=C2=
=A0you don=E2=80=99t have to sell stock anymore because things are fine.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">That doesn=E2=80=99t happen, but the=
 stock starts going up anyway, because Bed Bath is sort of a meme stock and=
 sometimes meme stocks go up for no reason, or for counterintuitive reasons=
, or just because they do something weird and make some news. And then you =
get to sell more stock and raise more money and keep this going for a while=
. Probably you eventually end up in Outcome=C2=A01 or Outcome 2, but I supp=
ose it is theoretically possible to be in this state forever.<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This sounds strictly=C2=A0better than filing f=
or bankruptcy in early February.=C2=A0Outcome 2 is straightforwardly good. =
Outcome 3 is, you know, weird, but sort of looks like Outcome 2. Outcome 1 =
is bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0you go bankrupt =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s no=C2=
=A0<em>worse=C2=A0</em>than filing for bankruptcy immediately, and in some =
ways it is better: You=E2=80=99ve raised some money, which means that your =
creditors get a better recovery, and you=E2=80=99ve delayed the bankruptcy =
so your employees can keep their jobs a while longer. Of course the money y=
ou raised comes from somewhere: It comes from people who=C2=A0<em>bought=C2=
=A0</em>stock from you on the way to zero, at prices higher than zero, and=
=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>might=C2=A0feel=C2=A0aggrieved that they threw the=
ir money into this bonfire. This is worse for=C2=A0<em>them=C2=A0</em>than =
just filing for bankruptcy immediately. But they are equity investors =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0realistically, they are meme-stock investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
 it=E2=80=99s their job to take weird risks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sounds pretty good, right?<a class=3D"footnote=
-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Why doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0every company do this, instead of filing=
 for bankruptcy? Well I think there are a few things that you need to manag=
e really carefully if you want to try this:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you just go out and=C2=A0<em>say=C2=
=A0</em>you=E2=80=99re going to do it, then investors will reasonably say =
=E2=80=9Cwait you=E2=80=99re selling stock until the stock goes to zero, wh=
y should I buy it at a price higher than zero?=E2=80=9D And so the stock co=
llapses to zero immediately, you never raise any money, and it doesn=E2=80=
=99t work. If you want to try this, you have to be somewhat opaque about it=
, so that investors actually buy the stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">Conversely, if you are=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>opaque about it, an=
d lots of investors buy the stock at high prices and you end up in Outcome =
1 anyway, those investors will sue you and the US Securities and Exchange C=
ommission will have a lot of questions and you will get in a lot of trouble=
. If you want to try this, you have to have=C2=A0<em>really good disclosure=
</em>, so that investors who=C2=A0buy the stock can=E2=80=99t say they were=
 deceived. You want that disclosure to be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0accurate and compl=
ete, but confusing? I dunno, it=E2=80=99s a weird=C2=A0needle to thread.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You need to be somewhat skillful abo=
ut selling the stock. You can=E2=80=99t just mash the sell button every day=
; you have to have a sense of the market, sell a lot when there=E2=80=99s a=
 lot of demand, step back when there isn=E2=80=99t. The price of the stock =
here is going to be a delicate thing, and it takes skill to wring as much m=
oney out of it as possible.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bed Bath took Hudson Bay up on the idea, I <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31011090.260442/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDcvYmVkLWJh=
dGgtYmV5b25kLXNvbGQtc29tZS1zdG9jaz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzMwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1=
