<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">RRP, TNB</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few years ago a bank named TNB USA Inc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0it stands for =E2=80=9CThe Narrow Bank=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 start=
ed up with a simple business model. It would take deposits from customers a=
nd park 100% of the deposits at the Federal Reserve. The Fed pays interest =
on bank reserves, so TNB would get=C2=A0interest from the Fed; it would pas=
s some of that interest along to its depositors and keep some to pay its ex=
penses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This business model had two benefits:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In 2018, when <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31011090.260442/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDktMDYvZmVkLXJlamVjdHMtYmFuay1mb3It=
YmVpbmctdG9vLXNhZmU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMzMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWF=
pbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzMwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb2=
5leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0abb4373" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  we first talked abo=
ut this</a>, banks were paying extremely low rates on deposits (single-digi=
t basis points), while the Fed was paying banks 1.95% interest on their res=
erves. By cutting out all of the normal expenses of banking (loan officers,=
 capital against loans, etc.), TNB could pass along most of that interest t=
o depositors and offer them a better interest rate than other banks.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">TNB was incredibly=C2=A0<em>safe</em>.=
 It would take no credit risk (all its deposits would be parked at the Fed)=
 and no interest-rate risk (all its liabilities and all its assets would be=
 demand deposits). If there was a run on TNB, it would just take its money =
out of the Fed and give it to its customers. It could never lose money or c=
ause a crisis. After the 2008 banking crisis, this had an obvious appeal.</=
li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To do this business model, TNB needed to open =
an account with the Fed (so it could park deposits there). And the Fed =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0said no.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Fed, it turns out, kind of hated The Narro=
w Bank. The problem is that TNB would be=C2=A0<em>too safe</em>. In 2019, t=
he Fed proposed a rule to, not quite=C2=A0<em>ban</em>=C2=A0narrow banking,=
 but to discourage it. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/31011090.260442/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMDgvdGhlLWZlZC12ZXJzdXMtdGhlLW5hcnJvdy1iYW5rP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA=
zMzAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMzMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBdf60076a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">  summarized the Fed=E2=80=99s concerns</a> at the tim=
e, saying=C2=A0that the Fed worried =E2=80=9Cthat narrow banks will take fu=
nding away from regular banks, making it harder for those banks to trade st=
ocks and bonds =E2=80=A6 and maybe even making it harder to make loans,=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthat having=C2=A0<em>too safe a bank=C2=A0</em>would be=
 bad for financial stability: In times of stress, everyone will flee from t=
he regular banks to the super-safe narrow banks, which will have the effect=
 of bringing down the regular banks.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This seems to be=C2=A0a theme in how the Fed t=
hinks about banks.=C2=A0<em>The Fed likes banks</em>. The Fed is broadly su=
pportive of the idea that banks should get deposits from customers and use =
those deposits to make loans. This is a very traditional, centuries-old ide=
a. This is just how banking works. But we know that banking is fragile; occ=
asionally =E2=80=94=C2=A0in 2008, in March 2023 =E2=80=94=C2=A0we are remin=
ded of it more forcefully. And so sometimes people come along with ideas =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0for narrow banking, for <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/31011090.260442/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMjQvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd2FudC10by1zdGF5LXBvcHVsY=
