PW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzMwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB1c553b42" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  stablecoins</a>,=C2=A0for universal =
Fed accounts, for <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
31011090.260442/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMTgtMDYtMTEvbWF5YmUtZG9sbGFycy1zaG91bGQtYmUtZGlnaXRhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzMwMj=
NfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fd=
GVybT0yMzAzMzAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB17b=
58303" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">  central bank digital currencies</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0to=
 make banking=C2=A0safer. =E2=80=9CI just want to have a checking account,=
=E2=80=9D they say, =E2=80=9Cso why should I have to put my money in a bank=
 that will take risks with it by making loans or buying long-term bonds? Wh=
y does my checking account have to represent a claim on a complicated syste=
m of debt? Why can=E2=80=99t it just be simple electronic dollars? The Fed =
issues dollars; why can=E2=80=99t my checking account just be=C2=A0<em>that=
?</em>=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31011090.260442/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTcvYmlnLWJhbmtzLXRydXN0LWZpcnN0LXJlcHVibGljLXdpdGg=
tdGhlaXItbW9uZXk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMzMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbC=
Z1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzMwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25le=
XN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb9dd5d63" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  answer to those questi=
ons</a> is sort of unsatisfying but also very beautiful: Banks are a=C2=A0w=
ay to get society to collectively take financial risks that people would no=
t individually take.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-13" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[13]</span>
</a>=C2=A0You want your checking account to be safe, and everyone wants the=
ir checking accounts to be safe, but somebody needs to lend people money to=
 start businesses or buy houses, and banks stand between the need for safe =
checking accounts and the need for risky debt financing and magically trans=
form risk into safety. And they do this through some combination of opacity=
 and mystery and implicit and explicit government backing. It will always b=
e fragile and frustrating, because it is in some deep sense a trick, but it=
=E2=80=99s a socially valuable trick.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There=E2=80=99s also another, more practical a=
nswer to those questions, which is that banks exist now and make a lot of l=
oans and employ a lot of people and are pretty important, and if we blew th=
em all up overnight that would be bad. If the Fed announced a new program t=
hat was like =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s a bank account but way better,=E2=80=
=9D then everyone might take their money out of the banks at once and they=
=E2=80=99d all collapse. Or even worse: Everyone=C2=A0<em>wouldn=E2=80=99t<=
/em>=C2=A0do that immediately, because they don=E2=80=99t care very much, b=
ut then one day people would start worrying about the banks, and=C2=A0<em>t=
hen=C2=A0</em>they=E2=80=99d all take their money out of their bank account=
s and put it in the cool new Fed account, and the banks would face a run at=
 the worst possible time, and<em>=C2=A0then</em>=C2=A0they=E2=80=99d all co=
llapse.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the Fed said no. But then it sort of allowe=
d narrow banking anyway, by accident, and now there=E2=80=99s a banking cri=
sis and narrow banking seems to be making it worse. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31011090.260442/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMzAvY2FzaC1zdGFz=
aGVkLWluLW1vbmV5LW1hcmtldC1mdW5kcy1ub3QtYmFua3MtZnVlbHMtcmVjZXNzaW9uLXJpc2s=
taW4td2FrZS1vZi1zdmI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMzMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbW=
FpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzMwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb=
25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7bc1ec56" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Alex Harris report=
s</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Money-market mutual funds are proving an irres=
istible place for investors to park their cash right now instead of banks.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The amount squirreled away in them has surged =
to more than $5 trillion and that risks becoming a problem for the US econo=
my if that grows too much and too quickly.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Encouraged by the higher rates that these fund=
s have been able to offer =E2=80=94 and their greater nimbleness in passing=
 on benchmark increases by the Federal Reserve over the past year =E2=80=94=
 savers have been shifting cash into them and out of traditional bank depos=
its. That was happening even before the recent banking turmoil, but the tre=
nd has been supercharged amid the collapse of Silicon Valley Bank and other=
 lenders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CDepositors are noticing=E2=80=9D the =
gap between what banks and money funds are offering in terms of interest ra=
tes, Barclays Plc money-market strategist Joseph Abate =C2=A0wrote in a not=
e to clients. =E2=80=9CWe expect flows into money funds to grow by several =
hundred billion dollars, heating up bank deposit competition.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An ongoing funding pinch for financial institu=
tions risks having knock-on effects for banks=E2=80=99 willingness to lend,=
 which in turn could weigh on the provision of loans to consumers and busin=
esses. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Money-market funds invest in a variety of cash=
-like instruments from Treasury bills to repurchase agreements, with a smal=
ler subset also putting funds to work in short-term corporate IOUs. Right n=
ow, though, a massive chunk of the total appears to be simply warehoused in=
 Fed facilities rather than finding its way back into the economy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Close to $2.3 trillion is stashed in the Fed=
=E2=80=99s reverse repo facility, which offers an annual rate of 4.80% for =
overnight cash and is primarily used by money-market funds. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If money funds continue to prove more attracti=
ve for savers than deposits, the downward pressure on banks=E2=80=99 reserv=
e levels may remain or even increase. Smaller US banks have seen deposits d=
rop, raising concerns about a reduction in lending to businesses and househ=
olds if the outflows continue. Fed figures show that while the biggest 25 b=
anks added some $120 billion in deposits in the week through March 15 =E2=
=80=94 the period when SVB failed =E2=80=94 smaller lenders lost $108 billi=
on from their accounts.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A money market fund that parks its cash at the=
 Fed=E2=80=99s reverse repo facility is more or less a narrow bank: It take=
s money from investors, it promises to return it on demand, it parks the ca=
sh at the Fed, it has the right to withdraw it from the Fed on demand, it g=
ets paid interest by the Fed, it passes most of that interest on to its inv=
estors and keeps a bit to pay its expenses. Like a narrow bank, it has few =
of the expenses of traditional banking (no loan officers, no branches, no c=
apital requirements<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-14" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[14]</span>
</a>), so it can pass along a lot of the interest to investors. Like a narr=
ow bank, it can offer investors a better interest rate than most banks. Lik=
e a narrow bank, it takes no credit risk or interest-rate risk, and it can =
tell investors =E2=80=9Cyour money is=C2=A0<em>much safer=C2=A0</em>here th=
an at a regular bank, since we just park 100% of it at the Fed.=E2=80=9D</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In an environment of rising interest rates =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0where banks have raised rates much more slowly than the Fed =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0that is attractive to depositors who want to earn a return. In =
an environment of banking worries =E2=80=94=C2=A0where banks have failed=C2=
=A0and uninsured deposits have, briefly, seemed to be at risk =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0that is=C2=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>attractive to depositors who want their =
money to be safe. And so money is leaving banks to go to money market funds=
 that park it at the Fed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the Fed=E2=80=99s worries were right! The =
Fed said no to TNB in 2019 because it worried that it would undermine tradi=
tional bank lending and that it would destabilize banks in times of trouble=
.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-15" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tra=
nsparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[15]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And now US regional banks seem to be destabilized, because people=
 are worried about their safety and have an attractive safe alternative. An=
d those banks are lending less. The=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31011090.260442/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xl=
cy9zbWFsbC1iYW5rcy1hcmUtbG9zaW5nLXRvLWJpZy1iYW5rcy10aGVpci1jdXN0b21lcnMtYXJ=
lLWFib3V0LXRvLWZlZWwtaXQtMTc4YWJiNDc_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zNQ/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBee88cae3" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Wall Street Journal=
 reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Banks need deposits to make loans; if deposits=
 fall, lending is almost sure to follow. What=E2=80=99s more, the recent tu=
rmoil could spur banks to start paying depositors higher interest rates, cr=
imping earnings and further cutting into their lending capacities. And the =
speed of the recent deposit runs=E2=80=94customers withdrew $42 billion fro=
m SVB in a day; Signature lost $18 billion=E2=80=94has bankers stockpiling =
cash.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The likely result, analysts and central banker=
s said, is a credit crunch.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf we lose that deposit base to the m=
oney-center banks, we can=E2=80=99t grow and lend out future dollars,=E2=80=
=9D said Brian Johnson, chief executive of North Dakota=E2=80=99s Choice Ba=
nk. =E2=80=9CCommunities can=E2=80=99t grow, and businesses can=E2=80=99t p=
rofit.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Johnson said that Choice=E2=80=99s bankers=
 and products hold their own against those of the megabanks, but that the l=
ender will never have the too-big-to-fail status that promises to shield de=
positors from losses. =E2=80=9CHow can I compete for new business with that=
 big enchilada out there?=E2=80=9D he said.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the biggest enchilada is the Fed, which di=
dn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to compete with the banks for deposits=
, but which ended up doing it anyway.</p>
